IT Budget




Viacom Inc. is a global entertainment content company. The company operates in two segments: Media Networks and Filmed Entertainment. The Corporate Systems unit is responsible for implementation of the Employee Systems and Solutions portfolio supporting Viacom as part of the Media… MoreViacom Inc. is a global entertainment content company. The company operates in two segments: Media Networks and Filmed Entertainment. The Corporate Systems unit is responsible for implementation of the Employee Systems and Solutions portfolio supporting Viacom as part of the Media & Technology Services (MTS) organization, which includes but is not limited to Human Resources, Payroll, Recruiting, Talent Management, Benefits and BPM systems. Viacom Inc. brands include BET, 345 Games, Famous Music, MTV, VH1, Nickelodeon, Nick at Nite, Comedy Central, CMT, Spike TV, TV Land, Paramount Pictures. The company was formed in June 2005 as a result of the former Viacom Inc.'s separation from CBS Corporation.
IT Priorities:
•Migrating software to updated systems.
•Data storage expansion.

IT Structure:
•The IT department for Viacom Inc. is based out of the company's headquarters in New York, NY. The Chief Information Officer (CIO) is responsible for the design, implementation, and operation of technology programs… MoreIT Priorities:
•Migrating software to updated systems.
•Data storage expansion.

IT Structure:
•The IT department for Viacom Inc. is based out of the company's headquarters in New York, NY. The Chief Information Officer (CIO) is responsible for the design, implementation, and operation of technology programs throughout the company's worldwide offices. The Chief Technology Officer supports the CIO and leads product development and programming enterprise-wide. 
•Viacom Inc. provides a shared infrastructure that is utilized by its lines of business. Since these divisions overlap, upper management can oversee IT functions for multiple divisions. The infrastructure group  is responsible for overseeing server and storage technology, data center operations,. network engineering, and backup systems architecture.
•The applications group oversees application initiatives, enterprise architecture, and applications development. The security and compliance group outline security initiatives within the compliance policy, they are also responsible for security policies, operations, as well as internal audit. 
•The company has various Vice Presidents who share responsibilities like information and knowledge management, product and media services, software quality assurance, data platform, quality management services, IT sourcing, and data services. 
•While Viacom shares most IT services across its smaller subsidiaries, Paramount Pictures, the company’s primary film division, operates relatively autonomously to the main IT department.
•Paramount’s IT department is primarily based in Los Angeles, CA, with its international arm centered in London, UK.
•Black Entertainment Television (BET), maintains smaller IT operations separate from the network headquarters. However, as of 2013, BET is in the process of merging its information technology department, from Washington, DC, to New York.
•MTV Games was shut down by Viacom in 2011.
•Viacom Inc. finalizes its IT budget in Q4.

IT Intelligence Snippets:

• Less than 30% of IT staff is dedicated to the sustenance of its ERP platform, and less than 30% of ERP support is outsourced to a third party.
• Expects around 25 releases/updates a year with its current ERP solution.
• Paramount Pictures has focused on initiatives, including, implementing a change management program, an iPad based mobile device program, a number of SAP module upgrades, and focusing on improving overall IT client support services.
• Viacom Inc. has expanded industry-specific, line of business, and productivity mobile applications and is planning to deploy analytics and plans to leverage third-party providers to address secure communications between mobile devices and the applications.
• Senior sources at Viacom Inc. indicate there are plans to increase spending in virtualization or to decrease spending in data center infrastructure. Virtualization is the top infrastructure priority for the company at this time.





